<!-- Pain Points -->
<section class="section bg-cream">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="section-header centered">
            <span class="section-eyebrow">The Real Costs of Inconsistent Irrigation</span>
            <h2>What's Actually Eating Your Margin</h2>
            <p>Most greenhouse operators know something is wrong. Here's what it usually comes back to.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="three-col-grid">
            <div class="pain-card">
                <div class="pain-icon">🪴</div>
                <h3>Uneven Plant Quality Costs You at Sale</h3>
                <p>When some benches get too much water and others too little, you end up with two types of product: premium plants and culls. The culls are a direct write-off — labor, input costs, and bench space, all wasted.</p>
                <div class="pain-solution">✓ Pressure-compensating drip emitters deliver the exact same volume to every container — from the first bench to the last.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="pain-card">
                <div class="pain-icon">👷</div>
                <h3>Hand Watering Burns Labor Hours</h3>
                <p>A skilled grower's time should go to plant health decisions, not pushing a hose. Hand watering also introduces human variability — some workers are thorough, others aren't, and your crop suffers for it.</p>
                <div class="pain-solution">✓ Automated drip systems pay for themselves within the first season purely on labor savings, consistently — not occasionally.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="pain-card">
                <div class="pain-icon">🧪</div>
                <h3>Fertilizer Waste and Nutrient Drift</h3>
                <p>Hand fertigation and broadcast application send nutrients into benches, floor drains, and the atmosphere — not into the root zone. You're buying fertilizer that benefits your floor, not your crop.</p>
                <div class="pain-solution">✓ Inline fertigation injects precisely dosed nutrients directly into the drip line — ±1% accuracy, zero floor runoff.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="pain-card">
                <div class="pain-icon">🍄</div>
                <h3>Wet Foliage and Root Rot</h3>
                <p>Overhead irrigation and misting at the wrong times keeps crowns and leaves wet — perfect conditions for botrytis, pythium, and other costly fungal diseases that spread bench to bench fast.</p>
                <div class="pain-solution">✓ Drip delivers water to the root zone only, keeping foliage dry and disease pressure dramatically lower.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="pain-card">
                <div class="pain-icon">📉</div>
                <h3>Crop Cycles Limited by Recover Time</h3>
                <p>When irrigation is inconsistent, crops take longer to reach sellable size and uniformity. That slows turnover, reduces cycles per year, and cuts into the revenue you could be generating from the same bench space.</p>
                <div class="pain-solution">✓ Optimized moisture and nutrition delivery accelerates growth — many growers see 2 full cycles where they previously managed 1.5.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="pain-card">
                <div class="pain-icon">⚡</div>
                <h3>No Visibility Until Something Goes Wrong</h3>
                <p>You walk in Monday morning and half the propagation house is wilted — or worse, flooded. Without real-time monitoring, problems in irrigation aren't caught until they've already killed crops.</p>
                <div class="pain-solution">✓ DripSphere OS™ monitors every zone in real time — alerting you to pump failures, pH drift, or missed irrigation cycles immediately.</div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

